<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="agent-dev-tuning">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>server-craft</domain>
    <summary>OS-level tuning for Claude Code agents on VPS: inotify limits, PAM file descriptors, swap, tmux linger, worktrees for parallelism, and resource cgroups.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>agent-dev</tag>
      <tag>inotify</tag>
      <tag>swap</tag>
      <tag>tmux</tag>
      <tag>worktree</tag>
    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Agent Dev Tuning for VPS Infrastructure</title>

    <summary>Server-side tuning checklist for running Claude Code and other AI agents on a VPS: raise inotify max_user_watches to 524288, configure PAM file descriptor limits, add 4-8GB swap with swappiness=10, set per-agent MemoryMax via systemd-run or cgroup scopes, use tmux with linger for session persistence, and use git worktrees for parallel agent execution without branch conflicts.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Defaults break silently under agent workloads: inotify exhaustion (8192 default watches vs 50k+ consumed by Claude Code on a large workspace) surfaces as "ENOSPC" errors that look like disk-full; missing swap causes OOM kills during LLM response processing; agents started in bare SSH sessions die on disconnect; two agents on the same branch overwrite each other's changes. These are infrastructure problems, not code problems — fix them at the OS/config layer once.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting up a new VPS for Claude Code agent work</item>
        <item>Seeing "ENOSPC: System limit for number of file watchers reached" errors</item>
        <item>Agent sessions dying when SSH disconnects</item>
        <item>Running multiple parallel agents on the same repository</item>
        <item>OOM kills during LLM API calls or large context processing</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Local macOS/Windows development — inotify is Linux-specific; macOS uses FSEvents</item>
        <item>Cloud-managed AI platforms (Replit, Codespaces) — these manage the environment for you</item>
        <item>Single short-lived agent sessions where full tuning is not worth the overhead</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="inotify-watch-limits">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set `fs.inotify.max_user_watches = 524288` as the first tuning step on any server running Claude Code. The kernel default (65536 or sometimes 8192) is exhausted on large workspaces, causing "ENOSPC: System limit for number of file watchers reached" errors that look like disk-full.</statement>
        <rationale>Claude Code creates one inotify watch per tracked file. A 50k-file repository with multiple git worktrees active can exceed the default limit immediately. The error message ("ENOSPC") is misleading — disk space is not the issue, the inotify watch table is full.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="inotify configuration">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Apply immediately + persist
echo 'fs.inotify.max_user_watches = 524288
fs.inotify.max_user_instances = 1024
fs.inotify.max_queued_events = 65536' | sudo tee /etc/sysctl.d/60-agent-dev.conf
sudo sysctl --system

# Verify
sysctl fs.inotify.max_user_watches
# fs.inotify.max_user_watches = 524288
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="pam-file-descriptor-limits">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set `nofile` to 65535 (soft) and 131072 (hard) for the agent user in `/etc/security/limits.d/`. The default soft limit of 1024 is hit immediately when Claude Code opens many files during workspace indexing.</statement>
        <rationale>Claude Code's workspace indexer, MCP servers, and subprocesses collectively open thousands of file descriptors. The PAM limit gates every process started in the user's session, including systemd user services.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="PAM file descriptor limits">
        <code lang="ini"><![CDATA[
# /etc/security/limits.d/nero-agent.conf
nero  soft  nofile    65535
nero  hard  nofile    131072
nero  soft  nproc     4096
nero  hard  nproc     8192
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="swap-for-llm-workloads">
      <rule>
        <statement>Create a 4–8 GB swap file on any server running LLM API calls, even if RAM is abundant. LLM response processing and large context windows cause memory spikes that can trigger OOM kills without swap.</statement>
        <rationale>The Python runtime allocating a 100MB JSON response tree from a large LLM context window is a transient spike. Without swap, the kernel OOM-kills the process. With 4 GB swap and swappiness=10, the spike lands in swap and the process completes normally.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="swap creation and configuration">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
sudo fallocate -l 4G /swapfile
sudo chmod 600 /swapfile
sudo mkswap /swapfile
sudo swapon /swapfile
echo '/swapfile none swap sw 0 0' | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
sudo findmnt --verify

# Set low swappiness: use RAM first, swap only under pressure
echo 'vm.swappiness=10' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.d/60-agent-dev.conf
sudo sysctl vm.swappiness=10
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="filesystem-noatime">
      <rule>
        <statement>Mount the root filesystem with `noatime` to eliminate write operations triggered by file reads. Agent workloads read thousands of source files; each read generates an atime write by default.</statement>
        <rationale>On every file read, the kernel updates the `atime` (access time) field, generating a write. With Claude Code reading 50k files during workspace indexing, this creates 50k unnecessary writes that slow SSD flash cells and compete with real write I/O.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="filesystem noatime mount option">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# /etc/fstab: add noatime to root mount options
# Before: UUID=xxx / ext4 defaults 0 1
# After:  UUID=xxx / ext4 defaults,noatime 0 1

# Apply without reboot
sudo mount -o remount,noatime /
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="tmux-session-persistence-with-linger">
      <rule>
        <statement>Enable `loginctl enable-linger` for the agent user so that tmux and systemd user services start at boot and survive SSH disconnects. Without linger, the user session ends on logout and all agent processes die.</statement>
        <rationale>When SSH disconnects, the login session ends and SIGHUP is sent to all processes in that session. Linger keeps a persistent user session alive at all times, so tmux survives reboots and disconnects without a screen/nohup workaround.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="tmux session persistence setup">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Enable linger (run once, as root or the user)
loginctl enable-linger nero

# Verify
loginctl show-user nero | grep Linger
# Linger=yes

# Create a named tmux session for agent work
tmux new-session -d -s work -n "claude"
tmux new-window -t work -n "logs"
tmux new-window -t work -n "monitor"

# Attach
tmux attach -t work
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="git-worktree-workflow-for-parallel-agents">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use `git worktree add` to give each parallel agent its own directory on a separate branch. Never have two agents on the same branch simultaneously — they will overwrite each other's uncommitted changes.</statement>
        <rationale>Git worktrees share the object store but each has its own index and HEAD. This means two agents can stage and commit changes independently without any locking or conflict, while sharing the full git history.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="git worktree workflow for agents">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Create worktree for a task
git worktree add ../nero-core-task-123 -b agent/task-123

# Agent works in the worktree
cd ../nero-core-task-123
# ... agent makes changes, commits ...

# List active worktrees
git worktree list

# Remove after merging
git worktree remove ../nero-core-task-123
git branch -d agent/task-123

# Prune stale worktrees (after the directory was deleted externally)
git worktree prune
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="resource-limited-agent-launcher">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use `systemd-run --user --scope` to apply `MemoryMax` and `CPUQuota` per agent session. This prevents one runaway agent from starving other services.</statement>
        <rationale>Claude Code's LLM API response parsing can spike to 2–4 GB RAM temporarily. Without a cgroup scope, that spike competes with PostgreSQL and the main API service. A per-agent scope caps the spike and preserves system stability.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="resource-limited agent launcher">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Launch Claude Code with resource limits in a named cgroup scope
systemd-run --user --scope \
    --unit="claude-agent-1" \
    --property=MemoryMax=4G \
    --property=CPUQuota=400% \
    -- tmux new-session -d -s agent-1 claude
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="claude-code-settings-json-allow-list">
      <p>A reasonable allow list for an agent doing infrastructure and Python development work. Place in `~/.claude/settings.json` or the project `.claude/settings.json`.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Claude Code settings.json for agent work">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[
{
  "permissions": {
    "allow": [
      "Bash(git *)",
      "Bash(python *)", "Bash(pip *)",
      "Bash(npm *)", "Bash(npx *)", "Bash(node *)",
      "Bash(docker *)", "Bash(docker compose *)",
      "Bash(systemctl --user *)", "Bash(journalctl *)",
      "Bash(curl *)", "Bash(rsync *)", "Bash(ssh *)",
      "Bash(ls *)", "Bash(mkdir *)", "Bash(cp *)", "Bash(mv *)",
      "Bash(cat *)", "Bash(grep *)", "Bash(find *)",
      "Bash(diff *)", "Bash(sort *)", "Bash(wc *)",
      "Bash(head *)", "Bash(tail *)", "Bash(make *)"
    ]
  }
}
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/60-agent-dev.conf" purpose="sysctl drop-in: inotify + memory + file descriptors"/>
      <template path="templates/claude-settings.json" purpose="Claude Code settings.json with common allow list"/>
      <template path="templates/agent-session.sh" purpose="tmux session setup: work + logs + monitor windows"/>
      <template path="templates/worktree.sh" purpose="Git worktree create/list/remove/clean management"/>
      <template path="templates/verify-agent-tuning.sh" purpose="Verify all tuning is applied, print OK/LOW per item"/>
    </templates>

